All Implemented Interfaces:

Direct Known Subclasses:
SortBasedDifference
public class SortBasedDifference<E>
extends AbstractCursor<E>

A sort-based implementation of the difference operator (input1 - input2). This operation can be performed in two different ways, namely the first realization removes an element of input1 if the same element exists in input2. The second way of processing removes all elements of input1 that match with an element of input2. This second approch implies that no duplicates will be returned by the difference operator, whereas the first solution may contain duplicates if the number of equal elements in cursor input1 is greater than that of input2.

The boolean flag all signals if all elements of cursor input1 that are equal to an element of input2 will be removed. In contrast to setting the flag to false, only one element will be removed. So depending on this flag the result of the difference operation can be a set, i.e., if all is true all duplicates will be removed in the output of this cursor, otherwise only one element is removed and the result may be a multi-set, i.e., duplicates may occur in the output.

Precondition: The input cursors have to be sorted!

Note: If an input iteration is given by an object of the class Iterator, i.e., it does not support the peek operation, it is internally wrapped to a cursor.

Example usage (1): 

   SortBasedDifference<Integer> difference = new SortBasedDifference<Integer>(
       new Enumerator(21),
       new Filter<Integer>(
           new Enumerator(21),
           new Predicate<Integer>() {
               public boolean invoke(Integer next) {
                   return next % 2 == 0;
               }
           }
       ),
       ComparableComparator.INTEGER_COMPARATOR,
       true,
       true
   );
   
   difference.open();
   
   while (difference.hasNext())
       System.out.println(difference.next());
   
   difference.close();
This example shows how to remove all even numbers from a given enumerator with range [0, 20]. A default instance of a default comparator for integers is used to compare the elements of the two inputs. This kind of comparator is also be chosen, if no comparator has been specified. The flag all, which is set to true does not have any effect in this case due to unique input elements.

Example usage (2): 

   difference = new SortBasedDifference<Integer>(
       new ArrayCursor<Integer>(1, 2, 2, 2, 3),
       new ArrayCursor<Integer>(1, 2, 2, 3),
       ComparableComparator.INTEGER_COMPARATOR,
       false,
       true
   );
   
   difference.open();
   
   while (difference.hasNext())
       System.out.println(difference.next());
       
   difference.close();
The first input cursor contains the elements {1, 2, 2, 2, 3}. The second cursor, that is to be subtracted, delivers the elements {1, 2, 2, 3}. So, in this case the flag all plays an important role. If it is false, as shown above, the sort-based difference operator delivers the element {2} as the only result. If it has been set to true the sort-based difference operator returns no elements.

Method Detail

open

public void open()
Opens the sort-based difference operator, i.e., signals the cursor to reserve resources, open input iterations, etc. Before a cursor has been opened calls to methods like next or peek are not guaranteed to yield proper results. Therefore open must be called before a cursor's data can be processed. Multiple calls to open do not have any effect, i.e., if open was called the cursor remains in the state opened until its close method is called.

Note, that a call to the open method of a closed cursor usually does not open it again because of the fact that its state generally cannot be restored when resources are released respectively files are closed.

close

public void close()
Closes the sort-based difference operator, i.e., signals the cursor to clean up resources and close its input cursors. When a cursor has been closed calls to methods like next or peek are not guaranteed to yield proper results. Multiple calls to close do not have any effect, i.e., if close was called the cursor remains in the state closed.

Note, that a closed cursor usually cannot be opened again because of the fact that its state generally cannot be restored when resources are released respectively files are closed.

hasNextObject

protected boolean hasNextObject()
Returns true if the iteration has more elements. (In other words, returns true if next or peek would return an element rather than throwing an exception.)

If input2 has no further elements all remaining elements of input1 can be returned. If the input cursors are sorted ascending, also the elements of input1 are returned, if they are smaller than the next element of input2. If the next element of input1 and input2 are equal, i.e., the given comparator returns 0, when comparing them, this element will not be returned. Depending on the flag all, all elements that are equal to the skipped element are skipped, too. So, if all is true the resulting cursor contains no duplicates. If the next element of input2 is larger than the next one of input1, input2 is consumed as long as this condition is fulfilled. If the input cursors are sorted descending the conditions explained above are negated and the computation runs the same way.

Specified by:
hasNextObject in class AbstractCursor<E>
Returns:
true if the sort-based difference operator has more elements.

remove

public void remove()
            throws java.lang.IllegalStateException,
                   java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException
Removes from the underlying data structure the last element returned by the sort-based difference operator (optional operation). This method can be called only once per call to next or peek and removes the element returned by this method. Note, that between a call to next and remove the invocation of peek or hasNext is forbidden. The behaviour of a cursor is unspecified if the underlying data structure is modified while the iteration is in progress in any way other than by calling this method.
